# AI Workforce Capacity Planner — Capstone

## Problem

Engineering leaders (VPs, team leads) at tech companies lack real-time, queryable visibility into workforce capacity. Forecasting who is available, who has the right skills, and where gaps will emerge across a project pipeline is currently a manual, spreadsheet-driven process.

## Target Users

VP of Engineering and team leads at tech companies. Questions are natural language. Output must be specific and actionable — names, dates, numbers, not generic advice.

## Scope

- **In scope**: Project staffing recommendations, skill gap analysis, capacity checks, headcount forecasting, what-if scenario analysis, project monitoring as scope changes
- **Out of scope**: Hiring decisions, performance management, compensation

## Three Iterations (Paradigm Progression)

| Iteration | Paradigm | Key Addition | Key Limitation |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Workflow Agent | Query classification + routing + domain prompt templates | Not grounded in org data |
| 2 | Workflow Agent + Retrieval | ChromaDB (employee profiles) + SQLite (allocations/projects) | Reactive — one question at a time |
| 3 | Autonomous Agent | Goal decomposition, tool-calling loop, episodic memory | Higher latency and cost |

## Tech Stack & Architecture

See `SPEC.md` sections 3 (Tech Stack) and 4 (Iteration Progression) for the authoritative reference.

**Current stack (v0):** LangGraph · LangChain · `gpt-4o-mini` · Streamlit · Arize  
**Iteration 2+:** adds ChromaDB (profiles) · SQLite (allocations) · query routing

## File Structure

This is the repo root. All paths are relative to it.

```
./
  app.py               # Streamlit UI
  planner.py           # LangGraph graph definition
  prompts.py           # system prompts and formatting functions
  data.py              # JSON loader + lookup helpers
  main.py              # CLI entry point
  data/                # mock org dataset (JSON files — edit to change org data)
    employees.json
    skills.json
    employee_skills.json
    projects.json
    project_requirements.json
    allocations.json
    time_off.json
  eval/
    test_cases.py      # labeled test questions + expected outputs
  .cursor/rules/       # Cursor AI rules (always applied in this repo)
```

## LLM Output Requirements

Every response must:
1. Use specific names and numbers from the data — never generic advice
2. Distinguish gap type: true skill gap vs. availability gap vs. coverage risk
3. Cite the source (employee name, project, allocation dates)
4. Include a RISKS section even when a match is found
